Best advice I think I can give is to absolutely keep trying to improve. As much as it is insulting to hear "just keep at it, you'll get better", it's the best way to help translate your thoughts onto paper more accurately. Of course, proper anatomy is paramount, so keeping up with that should still be important, otherwise you'll practice at drawing something wrong, then just get good at drawing it wrong more quickly. I'd say start with more simple designs then moving up to more detailed attempts, like not designing the specific hair fluff across the body and just working with a simple design, then attempting more detail once you get good practice in on the simpler drawings.

That's what worked for me, but then comes the problem that it isn't the solution for everyone. Wish you the best of luck with improving man. Keep trying, keep posting attempts, keep listening to feedback, and keep those drawings. Later on you'll see the progress you've made.

>Say I'm gonna give feedback in a little bit
>severalhourslater.jpg

Here's my two cents:

>Needs more exposition, and earlier
It took a little too long to establish your setting. Up until sword/guns/swordguns were introduced there wasn't any implication that this was a universe separate from our own (i.e identical but anthros are also here). On top of that, you waited until line 46 to point out the fact that the protagonist is the heir to the throne of a gang syndicate and it honestly felt like an afterthought when it was being mentioned; that kind of info definitely needs to be made sooner and elaborated on further for the story to flow smoother.

>Describe more
You mention "Sword pistols" several times, but just kind of assume that we as the reader know what you mean by that. Is that the name of a company that makes pistols, is that the designation given to that model of pistol, or is it literally just a pistol with a sword attached to it? Just a rule of thumb: when it comes to introducing something, assume the reader is a fucking idiot and be as descriptive as possible. The lion's purple car and guns are good examples of areas that could use more description. What kind of setting are you attempting to make this story in? The way you passively describe this car could be an easy way to create the setting in the viewer's mind. Does it look like a modern-day Ford Mustang, thus putting the story in a present-day, more realistic setting? Perhaps a sleek, yet jalopy-looking car, thus making it more steam-punky? Is it a hover-car, thus making it sci-fi/future-scape? Are his guns glocks? Revolvers? SMG/Uzis? Kalashnikovs? Muskets? Laser pistols? Subtle details like this are great ways to establish the story you're trying to tell in a more natural way.

ah this one's easy

Q: I need feedback to help improve, but there's no framework for review and editing, and the thread isn't an option. What do?

A: My advice? Get in touch with other writefags that would be willing to help, if you can get someone willing, you can send them a wip and ask for feedback on your work so far, so you know better what you're doing wrong, and what you're improving on as well. So far me and deco have been bouncing ideas and feedback off of eachother, and I even sent a scene wip towards Mous for his thoughts on it. Usually I can do this over pastebin since I have pro and can message, but if you don't have pro, it couldn't hurt to ask for a writefag with pro to message you via thread when it's quiet or past the bump limit. There's also pm's over discord if you don't want to wait an hour for someone to check their paste. You can't rely on the thread for good feedback most of the time since most people don't really have anything to say beyond what they felt about it: 'this is gud', but rarely I've seen legitimate criticism pop up. Going to other writefags is just far more reliable however.

also, updated the Q&A with this question. It was a quickie since it's a pretty easy answer from my experience.

-Coughing Fit

thread's still quiet, so any more takers? I won't promise that I can get to them immediately since not everything is as easy an answer as this one.
